# React Native Standards

## Component Structure

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD - Functional component with TypeScript
interface BookingCardProps {
  booking: Booking;
  onPress: (id: string) => void;
}

export const BookingCard: React.FC<BookingCardProps> = ({ 
  booking, 
  onPress 
}) => {
  return (
    <Pressable onPress={() => onPress(booking.id)}>
      <Text>{booking.destination}</Text>
    </Pressable>
  );
};
```

## State Management

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - Direct state mutation
user.name = 'New Name';

// ✅ GOOD - Immutable update
setUser(prev => ({ ...prev, name: 'New Name' }));
```

## API Calls

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD - Error handling + loading states
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

const fetchData = async () => {
  setLoading(true);
  setError(null);
  try {
    const data = await api.get('/bookings');
    setBookings(data);
  } catch (err) {
    setError('Failed to load bookings');
    logger.error('API error', err);
  } finally {
    setLoading(false);
  }
};
```

## Required Practices

- Use React Native Paper or NativeBase for UI
- Platform-specific code with `Platform.select`
- Handle keyboard avoiding views
- Implement pull-to-refresh
- Add loading and error states
- Optimize FlatList with `getItemLayout`
- Test on both iOS and Android
